1. Class
Definition

A class is a user-defined blueprint or template used to create objects. It defines the properties (attributes) and behaviors (methods) that objects of that class will have.

Think of a class as a design of a house. The design itself is not a house, but many houses can be built from that design.

2. Object
Definition

An object is an instance of a class. When a class is created, no memory is allocated. Memory is allocated only when an object is created.

Think of a class as a blueprint and an object as the actual house built from that blueprint

3. Attribute (Instance Variable / Data Member)
Definition

An attribute is a variable declared inside a class that stores information about an object. Attributes describe the state or characteristics of an object.

4. Function
Definition

A function is a block of code that performs a specific task. It can take input, process it, and return an output.

In Java, functions are generally called methods because every function must belong to a class.

5. Method
Definition

A method is a function that is defined inside a class. Methods represent the behavior of an object.

6. Method Overloading
Definition

Method Overloading is a feature in Java where multiple methods have the same name but different parameter lists.

The compiler determines which method to call based on the number or type of arguments passed.


// Class definition
class Student {

    // Attributes
    String name;
    int age;

    // Method
    void display() {

        System.out.println("Name: " + name);
        System.out.println("Age: " + age);
    }

    // Overloaded Method
    void display(String course) {

        System.out.println("Name: " + name);
        System.out.println("Age: " + age);
        System.out.println("Course: " + course);
    }
}

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        // Object creation
        Student s1 = new Student();

        // Assign values to attributes
        s1.name = "Sharmi";
        s1.age = 21;

        // Calling first method
        s1.display();

        System.out.println();

        // Calling overloaded method
        s1.display("Java Programming");
    }
}
